00:06:41.139 --> 00:06:42.139
Remember SHADING is all about RELATIVITY!

00:06:42.139 --> 00:06:43.360
So compare the tones of different areas of
your reference image or sitter.

00:06:43.360 --> 00:06:45.380
Be sure NOT to make the "smile line" look
too much like a "line".....just like the eyebrows,

00:06:45.380 --> 00:06:46.380
it is NOT a solid shape!

00:06:46.380 --> 00:06:47.380
Right now I am using a tortillion (blending
stump).

00:06:47.380 --> 00:06:48.960
It moves the graphite from the pencil more
quickly and efficiently than the paint brush.

00:06:48.960 --> 00:06:49.960
Tortillions are also very good at making lines.

00:06:49.960 --> 00:06:50.980
They are simply stumps of paper shapes like
pencils.

00:06:50.980 --> 00:06:51.980
The edges of the face are TRICKY.......YES,
they need to be darker in tone to seem rounded

00:06:51.980 --> 00:06:52.980
but they cannot appear as a solid line, or
else your drawing will not seem believable.

00:06:52.980 --> 00:06:53.980
NOTICE that I am using the technique of cross
hatching (line next to line) to apply the

00:06:53.980 --> 00:06:54.980
tones....then I am smudging it....followed
by another layer of hatching...or I could

00:06:54.980 --> 00:06:57.680
then create a highlight with the eraser.

00:06:57.680 --> 00:07:19.610
Be careful with the hairline.

00:07:19.610 --> 00:07:59.889
It is always a gradual transition of tone....Believe
it or not, even if a person is BALD, the top

00:07:59.889 --> 00:08:01.199
of the head is rounded and requires a gradual
gradation of tone!

00:08:01.199 --> 00:08:02.199
The areas around the eyes seemed dark before.....right?....See
what happens when you add darker tones?

00:08:02.199 --> 00:08:03.199
Shading is ALL ABOUT RELATIVITY!

